    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Highly unusual amphipods with flattened body shape, making them easily to mistake as being isopods (but have unmistakably amphipod limb structures). Antennae very short, walking limbs lack nippers and spayed out sideways to grip substratum. Abdominal appendages greatly reduced. Colour characteristic – red-brown with rows of flourescent bright blue dots along the back.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_271",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Between 4-7 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_272",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Still Bay to Namibia.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_273",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found in small groups clinging to the underside of boulders or to rock surfaces intertidally and on shallow reefs.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_274",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Biology unknown, but are slow moving and sedentary, walking slowly away when disturbed or exposed. Food unknown, but probably consists of benthic invertebrates such as hydroids, bryozoans or colonial ascidians, on which they are found.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_275",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like in all amphipods, the eggs are held in a marsupium between the walking legs of females and grow there into fully-developed juveniles before being released.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_276",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are only two species in this genus, both of which are endemic to South Africa. The other species, <i>T. hystrix</i>, has a series of strong upright dorsal projections along the centre of the back.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_277",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
